posts.name: Han Lu
posts.cooked:
Hello, I am Han from FRC4014 / FTC5206. I am looking for a place to fabricate for the 2024-2025 FRC and FTC seasons (water game!?!??!!?). Our school is unable to purchase and store any machines (as we are online), so the only machines we own is a drill press, my 3d printer, and some hand tools.

Right now, I need to fabricate some 1/4inch aluminum plates for our off-season swerve that I designed. I would also like to help with fabrication here in the Bay Area for next season. Does anyone know any good machine shops where I can get trained to use CNC’s and use it for next season?

posts.name: david
posts.cooked:
Look for some local maker spaces. Some have machining resources and might be willing to teach you how to machine.

Otherwise, cold contact whatever machine shops are in your area and ask them for a sponsorship, but maker spaces are more likely to train you.

posts.name: Zack W
posts.cooked:
You should checkout the noisebridge makerspace in SF!

Alternatively, I  noticed your team is based near Stanford University (idk how closely tied Stanford OHS is); you could try reaching out to the Stanford machine shop and seeing if they could help out

If those don’t work out, services like Fabworks (use promo code: FRC5026 ) or SendCutSend are a pretty good (but expensive) fallback

posts.name: Totally out of touch
posts.cooked:
I don’t know that I would call fabworks expensive if you faithfully add up material cost, amortized machine cost (or membership access), consumables (tools, spoil boards, coolant, etc…) and then your own time.

A team can do quite well with $1-2k per year at fabworks, especially if biasing towards thinner materials.

604 also has a neat method where they fabworks a single metal master, and then use a trim router with a pattern bit to cut out polycarb copies. The ones I saw looked as good as better than the average polycarb plate cut on an Omio router.

Oh, and use FRC581 for 5% off your order

posts.name: Eugene Fang
posts.cooked:
AdamHeard:

I don’t know that I would call fabworks expensive if you faithfully add up material cost, amortized machine cost (or membership access), consumables (tools, spoil boards, coolent, etc…) and then your own time.

A team can do quite well with $1-2k per year at fabworks, especially if biasing towards thinner materials.

Our Fabworks total for this year is $1300, including $150 of parts used exclusively for prototyping. This is comparable with the raw material cost we would’ve needed from the local metal market if we were to buy 1x2 ft sheets that fit on the omio we have limited access to.

(Use FRC604 for 5% off your order!)

posts.name: Alan Federman
posts.cooked: You are from Stanford California and have trouble finding facilities?  First, find a mentor from Stanford or SRI, a lot of Stanford computer engineering students are FIRST Alums. Next checkout the Maker Nexus, and start attending Homebrew Robotics Club meetings. If all else fails reach out to local teams, many will be willing to help you fabricate parts, or even donate older equipment. I would also contact Leland HS team 604 Quick Silver, they built a championship robot that had very little CNC on it.
